00 years, accounting has been an essential part of medical practice with significant moral, social and epistemological implications. Covering the period between 1500–2000, the book examines in short case studies the importance of calculative practices for medicine in very different contexts. Thus, Accounting for Health offers a synopsis of the extent to which accounting not only influenced medical practices over centuries, but shaped modern medicine as a whole.This book is relevant to United Nations Sustainable Development Goal 3, Good health and well-being.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAccounting. 0aMedicinexHistory. 0aSocial medicinexHistory. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh  aGood health and well-being.  abook-keeping.  acalculative practices.  ahealth economics.  ahealth insurance.  ahistory of medicine.  ahospital.  amedical knowledge.  amedical practice.  apharmaceutical industry.  avital statistics.1 aCastenbrandt, Helene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoyle, Barry M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFalk, Oliver, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFalk, Oliver, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGaudillière, Jean-Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHess, Volker, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHüntelmann, Axel C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHüntelmann, Axel C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMendelsohn, J. Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPorter, Theodore M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPranghofer, Sebastian, econtributor.